<div class="view" id="v-suggest">
<div class="hdr">
  <div class="ey" style="color:var(--sky)">SLC Architecture v5.0 · Module Suggestions</div>
  <h1 style="font-size:22px;">Modules worth <span style="color:var(--sky)">considering</span></h1>
  <p class="sub">Based on everything we've built and tested. Grouped into four tiers — add now, evaluate soon, consider for v2, and deliberate decisions. All grounded in what the stress tests revealed or what the solopreneur context demands.</p>
</div>

<div class="suggest-intro">
  <h2>How to read this</h2>
  <p>Tier 1 = gaps the stress tests proved are real. Tier 2 = modules that would close known friction points. Tier 3 = genuine value but not urgent. Tier 4 = worth discussing — may change the product category. None of these are automatic adds — every one requires your call.</p>
</div>

<div class="tier-label" style="color:var(--rose)">Tier 1 — Stress test proved these are missing · Add before or shortly after launch</div>
<div class="suggest-grid">
  <div class="sm-card tier-1">
    <div class="sm-top"><div class="sm-title">Proactive Order Status Notifications</div><span class="sm-domain dom-ops">ops</span></div>
    <div class="sm-body">When order status changes (paid → packing → shipped → delivered), auto-push update to customer via their original channel. Kills the "where is my order?" inbox noise.</div>
    <div class="sm-why"><strong>Why:</strong> Day-one sim showed chatbot handled these reactively. With 38 orders in 7 days (Scenario 1), that's ~80–100 unprompted status enquiries per campaign cycle. Each one interrupts Nong Fah or burns chatbot capacity on zero-value messages.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="sm-card tier-1">
    <div class="sm-top"><div class="sm-title">Post-Purchase Feedback Loop</div><span class="sm-domain dom-mkt">marketing</span></div>
    <div class="sm-body">3 days after delivery confirmed, chatbot sends 1-click rating. Negative → escalate to owner for service recovery. Positive → ask for public Google/Facebook review automatically.</div>
    <div class="sm-why"><strong>Why:</strong> Sentiment module currently has no first-party data — it only scrapes social. Every satisfied customer who never leaves a review is wasted signal. This closes the loop between delivery and the Sentiment module's intelligence layer.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="sm-card tier-1">
    <div class="sm-top"><div class="sm-title">Bank Reconciliation Prompt</div><span class="sm-domain dom-fin">finance</span></div>
    <div class="sm-body">Daily prompt asking Nong Fah to confirm bank balance against Auditor cash position. Marks dashboard cash as "reconciled" or "unreconciled" with a visual indicator. v2: bank feed API (SCB/KBank).</div>
    <div class="sm-why"><strong>Why:</strong> Day-one sim showed ฿490 discrepancy between Auditor and actual bank on day one. Every financial decision made on an unreconciled dashboard is a decision made on wrong numbers. This is the cheapest possible fix — a daily prompt.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="sm-card tier-1">
    <div class="sm-top"><div class="sm-title">Appointment + Booking Manager</div><span class="sm-domain dom-ops">ops</span></div>
    <div class="sm-body">For service-based SLC clients — consultation booking, slot management, reminder sends, cancellation handling. Integrates with the Chatbot for conversational booking via Line or IG.</div>
    <div class="sm-why"><strong>Why:</strong> Nong Fah is product-based so this didn't surface in her simulation. But a significant portion of your SLC clients will be service businesses (consultants, salons, tutors, freelancers). Without this, the Ops Engine has a hard gap for an entire client category. Diagnostic should gate-activate this for service profiles only.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="tier-label" style="color:var(--amber)">Tier 2 — Known friction points · Evaluate for inclusion before launch</div>
<div class="suggest-grid">
  <div class="sm-card tier-2">
    <div class="sm-top"><div class="sm-title">Multi-Currency + Tax Manager</div><span class="sm-domain dom-fin">finance</span></div>
    <div class="sm-body">Handles VAT calculation, withholding tax (WHT) for Thai businesses, multi-currency order logging for clients who sell internationally via Shopee, Lazada, or direct export.</div>
    <div class="sm-why"><strong>Why:</strong> The Basic Auditor currently has "basic tax-readiness export" as a sub-feature. That's insufficient for any Thai business doing real volume — VAT registration threshold is ฿1.8M/year, WHT applies to B2B payments. As clients grow on SLC, tax complexity grows with them. Addressing this early prevents Auditor becoming a liability.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="sm-card tier-2">
    <div class="sm-top"><div class="sm-title">Marketplace Sync</div><span class="sm-domain dom-ops">ops</span></div>
    <div class="sm-body">Two-way sync with Shopee, Lazada, TikTok Shop — orders pull into SLC automatically, inventory updates push out, revenue flows into Auditor. One operations centre regardless of which platform the sale came from.</div>
    <div class="sm-why"><strong>Why:</strong> Most Thai product solopreneurs sell across 2–4 platforms simultaneously. Right now, a Shopee order is invisible to SLC. Nong Fah has to manage Shopee separately, then reconcile manually. Without marketplace sync, the "one web app" vision breaks the moment clients have a Shopee store — which is almost all of them.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="sm-card tier-2">
    <div class="sm-top"><div class="sm-title">Subscription + Recurring Revenue Manager</div><span class="sm-domain dom-fin">finance</span></div>
    <div class="sm-body">Manage subscription products or retainer clients — recurring billing schedule, payment status tracking, renewal reminders, churn prediction based on engagement drop before renewal date.</div>
    <div class="sm-why"><strong>Why:</strong> The Pivot Suggester already recommends "model pivot to subscription" as a high-value strategic move. But if a client takes that advice and switches to subscriptions, SLC has no module to run it. The strategy module and the operations module need to agree on what's possible to build.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="sm-card tier-2">
    <div class="sm-top"><div class="sm-title">AI Pricing Optimiser</div><span class="sm-domain dom-mkt">marketing</span></div>
    <div class="sm-body">Monitors competitor pricing, demand signals, and inventory levels in real time. Suggests dynamic price adjustments — raise when demand is high and stock is low, promote when stock is excess and demand is soft.</div>
    <div class="sm-why"><strong>Why:</strong> Pricing Strategy (Stage 1) sets the price at launch. But markets move. @GlowThai's contamination scandal in Scenario 3 was an opportunity for Nong Fah to raise prices while competitors were damaged — and SLC had no module to see or suggest it. Dynamic pricing is what separates a planning tool from an operating intelligence.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="tier-label" style="color:var(--sky)">Tier 3 — Genuine value, not urgent · Consider for v2</div>
<div class="suggest-grid">
  <div class="sm-card tier-3">
    <div class="sm-top"><div class="sm-title">Loyalty + Rewards Programme</div><span class="sm-domain dom-mkt">marketing</span></div>
    <div class="sm-body">Points accumulation, tier tracking, reward redemption — managed via Chatbot. Customers check balance via Line. Automatically integrates with Dynamic CRM segmentation and Promo Rules Engine.</div>
    <div class="sm-why"><strong>Why:</strong> The Customer Retention module identifies who is at churn risk. The Dynamic CRM can segment by loyalty tier. But there is no mechanism to reward loyalty — the modules have the intelligence but no action layer. A lightweight points system gives the retention intelligence somewhere to go.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="sm-card tier-3">
    <div class="sm-top"><div class="sm-title">Business Health Score</div><span class="sm-domain dom-fin">finance</span></div>
    <div class="sm-body">A single composite score (0–100) computed from revenue trend, cash position, inventory health, churn rate, campaign ROI, and task completion rate. Updates weekly. Shown prominently on the Performance Dashboard.</div>
    <div class="sm-why"><strong>Why:</strong> Right now the Performance Dashboard shows individual metrics — revenue, pipeline, cash, tasks. A solopreneur can look at a green cash balance and a red churn rate and not know which to act on first. A single score collapses the complexity into one number with a drill-down — "Your score dropped 8 points this week. Main cause: churn rate increased."</div>
  </div>
  <div class="sm-card tier-3">
    <div class="sm-top"><div class="sm-title">Competitor Monitoring</div><span class="sm-domain dom-mkt">marketing</span></div>
    <div class="sm-body">Tracks 3–5 named competitors — pricing changes, new product launches, social media activity, review sentiment. Alerts when a competitor drops price or launches something relevant.</div>
    <div class="sm-why"><strong>Why:</strong> Market Intelligence (Stage 1) does a one-time competitor map at launch. Scenario 3 showed that real-time competitor events (the @GlowThai scandal) create market opportunities that SLC currently cannot see or act on. Continuous monitoring turns a static snapshot into a live intelligence feed.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="sm-card tier-3">
    <div class="sm-top"><div class="sm-title">AI Financial Advisor</div><span class="sm-domain dom-fin">finance</span></div>
    <div class="sm-body">Monthly analysis of Auditor data — identifies trends, flags anomalies, and provides plain-language recommendations: "Your cost of goods rose 12% while revenue grew 3% — margin is compressing. Here are three options."</div>
    <div class="sm-why"><strong>Why:</strong> The Auditor shows what happened. The Pivot Suggester shows what to do in a crisis. There is nothing in between — a module that proactively reads financial trends and makes recommendations before a crisis develops. This is the "CFO in your pocket" positioning that makes SLC genuinely different from accounting software.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="tier-label" style="color:rgba(255,255,255,0.3)">Tier 4 — Deliberate decisions · These change the product category</div>
<div class="suggest-grid">
  <div class="sm-card tier-4">
    <div class="sm-top"><div class="sm-title">HR + Payroll Lite</div><span class="sm-domain dom-ops">ops</span></div>
    <div class="sm-body">Basic payroll calculation for 1–5 staff, social security contribution tracking, leave management, simple employment record keeping.</div>
    <div class="sm-why"><strong>Why this is a deliberate decision:</strong> Adding payroll moves SLC from a solopreneur tool into SME territory. That is a different regulatory environment (Labour Protection Act, Revenue Department compliance), a different support burden, and a different liability profile. If your diagnostic starts routing businesses with 3–5 employees, this gap will surface fast. Decide whether SLC is for true solopreneurs (0–1 staff) or small teams (up to 5) — that decision gates whether this module belongs.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="sm-card tier-4">
    <div class="sm-top"><div class="sm-title">B2B Sales + Proposal Manager</div><span class="sm-domain dom-comm">comms</span></div>
    <div class="sm-body">For solopreneurs selling to businesses (not consumers) — proposal builder, contract management, milestone billing, client portal for project status.</div>
    <div class="sm-why"><strong>Why this is a deliberate decision:</strong> ACERIS itself is B2B. Some of your SLC clients will be consultants, agencies, or service businesses with B2B clients. But the entire SLC architecture — Chatbot, Lead Capture, CRM Lite, Invoicing — is designed around B2C consumer behaviour. Serving B2B clients well requires a different relationship model, longer sales cycles, and different CRM logic. Either scope it explicitly in or out of the diagnostic.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="sm-card tier-4">
    <div class="sm-top"><div class="sm-title">White-label / Franchise Mode</div><span class="sm-domain dom-ai">platform</span></div>
    <div class="sm-body">Allow a solopreneur who has grown into a franchisor to give each franchisee their own SLC instance, with a master dashboard showing aggregate performance across all locations.</div>
    <div class="sm-why"><strong>Why this is a deliberate decision:</strong> The Pivot Suggester already recommends "franchise model" as a scale pivot. If a client takes that advice, they will outgrow SLC as it currently stands — they need a platform that serves multiple operators, not one. This is a multi-tenancy architecture decision, not a module addition. Worth flagging now so the technical architecture doesn't prevent it later, even if you don't build it in v1.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="sm-card tier-4">
    <div class="sm-top"><div class="sm-title">AI Agent Builder (No-Code)</div><span class="sm-domain dom-ai">platform</span></div>
    <div class="sm-body">Let SLC clients build their own simple AI agents without code — custom FAQ bots for their business, automated follow-up sequences, internal task automations — using a drag-and-drop interface.</div>
    <div class="sm-why"><strong>Why this is a deliberate decision:</strong> This moves ACERIS from a product company to a platform company. Your current moat is that SLC knows the client's business before they log in. An agent builder removes that moat — clients configure it themselves, which is exactly what you positioned against. Only consider this if the vision is to become an infrastructure provider, not a co-pilot provider. These are different businesses.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="arch-decisions">
  <h3>Architecture decisions required from sync test — confirm before building</h3>
  <div class="ad-grid">
    <div class="ad-item"><div class="ad-q">Attribution model</div><div class="ad-body">First-touch vs last-touch when multiple campaigns active simultaneously.</div><div class="ad-rec">Recommend: last-touch default (code at purchase). First-touch as toggle in Analytics settings.</div></div>
    <div class="ad-item"><div class="ad-q">Sentiment pause threshold</div><div class="ad-body">At what drop level does the system push a campaign pause recommendation to owner?</div><div class="ad-rec">Recommend: 25 percentage points in a 4-hour window. Nong Fah sets her own threshold.</div></div>
    <div class="ad-item"><div class="ad-q">Dynamic CRM sync frequency</div><div class="ad-body">How often do segment memberships refresh after a status change?</div><div class="ad-rec">Recommend: 30-minute maximum. Real-time ideal but has infrastructure cost implications.</div></div>
    <div class="ad-item"><div class="ad-q">KOL audience fit thresholds</div><div class="ad-body">At what overlap % does Campaign Builder warn vs hard block?</div><div class="ad-rec">Recommend: warn at &lt;50% fit, block at &lt;25% fit with manual override option.</div></div>
  </div>
</div>
</div>

